#cottagecheese recipes are ALL the rage right now… protein advantage, and when blended up- oh so creamy! I don’t do dairy unless it’s organic, grass-fed… all the things. This recipe is for my hubby, as he loves a good macro friendly meal that tastes like it’s not-so- much lol!!!! 

RECIPE MADE BULK FOR 5 MEALS
(So do the math if you would like it broken down differently- many of you may want lower lunch/dinner calories than his need) 
Each meal for him includes 3 burritos, all equaling to= 
Calories: 774
Protein: 79g
Fat: 38
Carbs: 27

Recipe—

2 C cottage cheese
1 C Parmesan cheese 
2 TBSP ranch seasoning 
4 TBSP olive oil
26oz chicken breasts
12 cooked bacon strips 
15 @josephspitabread tortillas 

Mix the sauce ingredients, then throw in chicken and bacon. Divide evenly amongst 3 tortillas per meal (15 total). I like to spray a little avo oil and pop ‘em on a pan to stick together. 

For easy prep, my hubby likes the premade chicken squares from Costco… if I made these for myself, it would be organic. You choose based off of preference :)

I probably could have made my presentation a bit prettier, but honestly… my taste buds thought this was beautiful! 
This has absolutely swerved my sweet tooth- especially at 34 weeks pregnant! So clean- but so yummy. I didn’t track the macros on this, because that wasn’t the point for this one :) 

Details:
-3 TBSP organic chia seeds 
-2/3 C organic almond milk @califiafarms 
-1/2 tsp vanilla ext or a couple drops vanilla stevia @sweetleaf 
-1 TBSP maple syrup 
-pinch of salt
-1 chopped mango 
-organic coconut cream
-organic honey 

1. Mix up chia, milk, vanilla, maple syrup and salt
2. Refrigerate for 2+ hours 
3. In a cup, layer chia mix, coconut cream, honey and mango in whatever order you choose 🤍

MILES CIRCUIT! 
*raw and real! I haven’t showered, haven’t put a real outfit on, but I wanted to show in real time what we are doing* Going on 40.5 weeks, and working to get her out ;) 

Our midwives recommended we start the Miles Circuit to ensure positioning, further early labor, and practice breathing before our home birth. 

Try it if you’re close to due date, or over, to get baby movin! Each step is a full 30 mins, for 90mins total. 

1. “Open Knee Chest” - looks similar to child’s pose, but don’t do that ;). Drop chest all the way to the floor with your legs outside of your booty as high as you can, legs spread to get around your belly. Use this time to practice your breathing and get fully relaxed. I can’t lie- this step was the hardest for me, my shoulders felt tight from weightlifting, 30 mins without moving plays with my head, but once I got into it- I learned a lot about those low breathing techniques we need for a natural birth. 
This allows baby to scoot out of the pelvis and give room to shift their head position. It also induced contractions for me :) 

2. “Exaggerated Side Lying Position” - By far the easier part of this, and feel free to fall asleep if you want! Lay on your side, getting your top leg as high as you can, bottom leg should be straight. And lay your torso over onto your belly as far as you can. Choosing just one side is fine, but if you repeat this later on- choose the other side. Doesn’t feel like you’re doing much, but take this time to relax and ready to get moving in step 3. 

3. “Get Up and Moving” - you e got options here! You can either choose one, or circuit through a couple like I did! Curb walking, lunges, side stepping up the stairs (2 at a time), hula on a birthing ball, etc. 
Pro-tip: your movements should be at a right angle, as knees over toes will close the pelvis! Positive shin angle is okay, but nothing further.

Welcome to the world, my love 🤍 
Darya Sarai Akradi was born in our home at 4:47pm on Thursday, 9/14… weighing 7lbs, 1oz and 20in long. 
All three of us are doing well and soaking in all the first time moments. 

As many know, we chose to do a natural home birth… and while her overdue adventure kept us on our toes, we kept pushing for as many natural opportunities as possible without folding. 
On Wednesday (9/13), intense contractions started and I believed to be in early labor. However, things stalled and the next morning I was on a 2 mile adventure with the boys 🐕 and went about my day as normal. Freddy and I set up the bedroom for birth just in case. 

At 11:22am on 9/14 I had my first contraction where I was like “yep it’s back and it’s happening”… 
I went upstairs to shower and I wanted to put a little makeup on so I could feel good about myself and feel fresh to meet baby!But- things progressed SO quickly at that point- I didn’t even have my hair up until I was puking 🤢 in it. 

Contractions quickly moved from 8mins apart to 4 mins apart. My water broke at 1:45pm and contractions hit 2 mins apart. We didn’t even know if the midwives or the doula would be here before I transitioned… (transition is when I start pushing)...

My Doula showed up at 2:30 and midwives at 3:30, got into the pool at 3:45 for transition … started pushing…
and then 4:47 Freddy caught her in his arms. 

I have never experienced something so intense or so invigorating all at once. The quick timeline made for a bit more pain than anticipated, but I wouldn’t have it any other way. 
I had always planned to use hypnobirthing as a tool to walk myself through the pain, but I never started the learning process early enough. I did, however, use the birth comb and it was one of the absolute best tools. Freddy was my grounding light through every single contraction. He often reminded me “it’s just one intense interval… just like in your classes”… and he was right- just one at a time.

It doesn’t have to be just one or the other…. Maybe it’s both. Integrating co-sleeping into whatever night routine you have, just might save you, mama! Whether it’s just a few more minutes of sleep, or less worrying through the night, doing it for YOU is why you should. 

Every routine (& every baby) is different. But we start our night with lights dimmed low, soothing to sleep and straight into the bassinet. This gives mama (& dad) some time unattached and free to get some zzz’s alone. When that first feed comes along, I scoop her up, let her latch, and I go back to sleep. 
I don’t leave the bed, or the room, even my sleep sometimes. When baby girl is done with her meal, she stays cuddled in close until morning. 

Also check out my @snuzusa Snuz Pod bassinet that ROCKS…. Whenever Darya startles herself or starts to wake, I lean over and rock her back to sleep without even moving from bed. This is the 2nd bassinet I got, so I thought this was pretty cool when I first used it!!!
